{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657351"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:26:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:26:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.76,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12078"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83305"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12078"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"779"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28529"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28531"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83305"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a left foot ulcer which has been present for three months. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 15 years ago, with known peripheral neuropathy and hypertension. His medications include metformin, gliclazide, and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The ulcer is 2 cm in diameter with well-demarcated borders, located on the plantar surface of the foot beneath the first metatarsal head (Image). There is thick surrounding callus formation. The ulcer base appears clean with minimal granulation tissue. Both dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulses are easily palpable with an ankle-brachial index of 1.1. Monofilament testing reveals absent sensation in both feet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of this ulcer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arterial","Infective","Neuropathic","Trauma","Venous"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic neuropathic ulcer in the context of long-standing diabetes. \u003Cstrong\u003ENeuropathic\u003C/strong\u003E ulcers typically occur at pressure points on the plantar surface of the foot, particularly under the metatarsal heads. They are characterised by well-demarcated borders, surrounding callus formation, and are typically painless due to peripheral neuropathy. The normal ankle-brachial index and easily palpable pulses indicate adequate arterial supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial\u003C/strong\u003E ulcers are characterised by poor granulation tissue, pain that is worse at night and relieved by dependency, and are often associated with absent pulses or reduced ankle-brachial index. The presence of normal pulses and ankle-brachial index make arterial insufficiency unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous\u003C/strong\u003E ulcers typically occur in the gaiter area (just above the ankle) and are characterised by irregular borders, significant granulation tissue, and surrounding haemosiderin staining. The location and absence of these features make a venous ulcer unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrauma\u003C/strong\u003E would typically have a clear history of injury and would not explain the characteristic features of neuropathy such as callus formation and sensory loss. The chronic nature and typical features make trauma unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfective\u003C/strong\u003E ulcers would typically show signs of surrounding cellulitis, purulent discharge, or systemic symptoms. While infection can complicate any type of ulcer, it is not the primary cause in this case given the characteristic features of diabetic neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of neuropathic ulcers focuses on pressure offloading (often with total contact casting), regular debridement of callus, optimising glycaemic control, and careful monitoring for infection. Patient education about foot care and regular podiatry review are essential preventive measures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neuropathic ulcers typically occur at pressure points on the foot and are painless due to diabetic peripheral neuropathy.","The presence of callus formation around an ulcer is characteristic of neuropathic ulcers.","Normal pulses do not exclude a neuropathic ulcer, as the pathology is primarily neurological rather than vascular."],"references":["Grey et al. Venous and arterial leg ulcers. BMJ. 2006. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1363917/","Falanga V, Isseroff RR, Soulika AM, Romanelli M, Margolis D, Kapp S, Granick M, Harding K. Chronic wounds. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2022 Jul 21;8(1):50. doi: 10.1038/s41572-022-00377-3. PMID: 35864102; PMCID: PMC10352385.","Star A. Differentiating Lower Extremity Wounds: Arterial, Venous, Neurotrophic. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2018 Dec;35(5):399-405. doi: 10.1055/s-0038-1676362. Epub 2019 Feb 5. PMID: 30728656; PMCID: PMC6363550."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21524"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21524"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/83FlWyS19oh3Lic3UuELUwy3R9Etd5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/83FlWyS19oh3Lic3UuELUwy3R9Etd5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":346}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-03T13:08:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-03T13:09:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12078"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83305"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"